# 7K UI/UX Master Framework (MF)

Version: 1.0
Scope: Entire launcher + all 7K apps
Rule: **No plain/default UI controls in final surfaces**. Every component must use 7K design tokens, motion, touch response, and state styling.

---

## 1) Core principles

1. Branded, not generic.
2. Consistent across launcher + every 7K app.
3. Touch-first (thumb ergonomics, clear feedback).
4. Motion with meaning (not decorative noise).
5. Accessibility is first-class, not optional.
6. Performance-aware visual richness.

---

## 2) Non-negotiable UI policy

- Disallow unstyled platform defaults in production UI:
  - `android.R.layout.simple_*`
  - plain `Button`, plain `Spinner`, plain `Switch` without 7K skin wrappers
- Every control must map to a custom 7K component family:
  - `7KButton`, `7KSwitch`, `7KDropdown`, `7KCard`, `7KListItem`, `7KSheet`, `7KDialog`
- Every screen must consume tokenized style values only (no ad-hoc hardcoded colors/sizes).

---

## 3) Design token system

## 3.1 Color tokens

- `color.bg.base`
- `color.bg.elevated`
- `color.bg.glass`
- `color.surface.primary`
- `color.surface.secondary`
- `color.text.primary`
- `color.text.secondary`
- `color.text.inverse`
- `color.brand.primary`
- `color.brand.secondary`
- `color.brand.accent`
- `color.state.success`
- `color.state.warning`
- `color.state.error`
- `color.state.info`
- `color.focus.ring`
- `color.border.default`
- `color.border.strong`

## 3.2 Typography tokens

- `type.display.l`
- `type.display.m`
- `type.title.l`
- `type.title.m`
- `type.body.l`
- `type.body.m`
- `type.body.s`
- `type.label.l`
- `type.label.m`
- `type.mono.s`

## 3.3 Spacing and size tokens

- spacing scale: 4/8/12/16/20/24/32/40
- min touch target: **48dp** (preferred 52dp for key actions)
- corner radii: 8/12/16/20/28
- icon sizes: 16/20/24/32/40/48/56
- stroke widths: 1/1.5/2dp

## 3.4 Elevation + glass tokens

- `elevation.0/1/2/3/4`
- `glass.blur.light/medium/heavy`
- `glass.tint.day/night`
- fallback surfaces for low-end devices when blur disabled

---

## 4) Interaction model

## 4.1 Touch response

Every tappable element must define:
- press-in scale: 0.98
- release spring back: 120–180ms
- haptic tier: none/light/medium/heavy (context-based)
- visual pressed state: tint or glow shift

## 4.2 Gesture semantics

- Gesture outcomes must be deterministic.
- Every gesture action with external target requires explicit setup UI.
- Gesture conflict map must be maintained (home vs drawer vs sidebar).

## 4.3 Drag/drop behavior

- consistent drag shadow style (rounded + glow)
- magnetic snap zones (dock/sidebar/home grid)
- live insertion indicator
- drop animation (position + scale + fade)
- undo snackbar for destructive drops/removals

---

## 5) Component library spec

## 5.1 Buttons

- variants: primary/secondary/ghost/destructive
- sizes: compact/default/large
- states: default/hover/pressed/disabled/loading

## 5.2 Dropdowns / pickers

- custom sheet-based selector preferred over plain spinner
- search-enabled for long lists
- section headers + icon support

## 5.3 Cards and list rows

- unified 7K card primitives with density modes
- strong selected/focused state
- optional swipe actions

## 5.4 Dialogs and bottom sheets

- custom header, branded action row
- safe-area + keyboard-aware layouts
- destructive confirmations use explicit risk styling

## 5.5 Inputs

- floating/compact labels
- helper/error text states
- validation feedback on blur + submit

## 5.6 Switches/toggles/sliders

- custom thumb/track colors
- expanded hit targets
- immediate visual + optional haptic confirmation

---

## 6) Launcher-specific UX rules

- Home icon sizing, drawer icon sizing, dock icon sizing must all resolve from shared token mapping.
- Sidebar and dock actions require contextual menus with clear language.
- Privacy-locked app launch must always show branded auth gate.
- Widget add/configure flow must be cancel-safe and recoverable.
- Empty states must be designed (not blank placeholders).

---

## 7) App-level UX rules (all 7K apps)

- Each app must inherit 7K shell style: top bar, card style, buttons, sheets, and typography scale.
- No app may use plain Android default dropdown/button/list tile in final UI.
- Shared navigation and action affordances across ecosystem apps.
- Cross-app intents must preserve motion continuity where possible.

---

## 8) Accessibility baseline

- contrast ratios:
  - body text >= 4.5:1
  - large text >= 3:1
- touch target >= 48dp
- screen reader labels for all actionable UI
- motion-reduction mode for users with animation sensitivity
- dynamic text scaling support with layout resilience

---

## 9) Performance and quality constraints

- keep frame pacing stable under gesture-heavy interactions
- adaptive effects tiering by device capability
- avoid overdraw-heavy layered effects on low-end hardware
- component render budgets per screen must be profiled

---

## 10) Implementation architecture

- `Theme/Tokens`: single source of truth (colors, typography, dimensions, motion)
- `Components`: reusable 7K UI kit package
- `Patterns`: screen templates (settings/list/detail/dashboard/dialog)
- `Lint Rules`: flag usage of banned default UI patterns

---

## 11) QA checklist for “no generic UI” compliance

A screen passes only if:
- all controls are tokenized
- no default spinner/button/list row is visible
- touch feedback is present and consistent
- drag/drop states are clear
- accessibility checks pass
- dark/light themes both polished

---

## 12) Rollout phases

1. Foundation: tokens + core components
2. Launcher migration: home/drawer/dock/sidebar/settings
3. 7K app migration: ecosystem apps in batches
4. Compliance pass: lint + screenshot diffs + UX QA

---

## 13) Done definition

“Done” means:
- zero plain default controls in production launcher + 7K apps,
- all key flows use branded components,
- touch/drag/motion/accessibility/performance baselines pass,
- design language feels unified and premium end-to-end.
